    <text>
        <body>
            <pb n="1"/>
            <p rend="align(right)">
                <placeName>Danville, Pa</placeName>
            </p>
            <p rend="align(right)">
                <date>January 6/63</date>
            </p>
            <p>
                <addressee>Rev Isaac Leeser</addressee>
            </p>
            <p rend="indent(2)">
                <placeName>Phila</placeName>
            </p>
            <p>Dear Sir!</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">It affords me a great Deal<lb/> of pleasure of having
                opportunity<lb/> again to write a few lines<lb/> to you for which I hope you<lb/>
                will excuse me. Above all I have<lb/> the pleasure to announce to<lb/> you that I am
                    <sic>determint</sic><lb/> to <sic>quite</sic> Hazanship <add>?</add>
                <date>April 1/63</date><lb/> and <sic>summonce</sic> something else<lb/> for the
                support of my beloved<lb/> family. I have faithfully<lb/> discharged my Duties for
                seven<lb/> years &amp; three months, have<lb/> spent all my time for the<lb/>
                welfare of the Congregation,</p>
            <pb n="2"/>
            <p rend="indent(1)">But I feel myself bound<lb/> now to quit, not because<lb/> I do not
                love my religion<lb/> any more or feel to be<lb/> ashamed to be a Hebrew
                minister<lb/> but because I do not and<lb/> never will bow down<lb/> for the
                Almighty Dollar<lb/> who lives and <add>?</add> all<lb/> Jewish Hearts. I feel
                assured<lb/> that I can make my living<lb/> in any other business and<lb/> more
                honorably than to be the<lb/> minister of a Congregation<lb/> who is governed only
                by two<lb/> or three who violate the laws<lb/>
                <sic>dayly</sic> who on <date>Yom Kipur</date><lb/> had their meatshop open<lb/> and
                the wagon of one came<lb/> before the Synagogue Door<lb/> for Orders. Dear Sir!<lb/>
                I know the most do not<lb/> like to see me leave; but</p>
            <pb n="3"/>
            <p>it can not be helped.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">In the spring when I come<lb/> to <placeName>Phila</placeName> I
                will settle my<lb/> account with you. Do not<lb/> be afraid I am still a
                faith<lb/>ful servant of the Lord.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">For curiosity I will remark<lb/> to you that last week,
                    <placeName>Danville</placeName><lb/> was honored by a new Jewish<lb/> Rabbi, so
                he signed his name.<lb/> The <persName>Rev Dr M. Delbanco</persName>,<lb/> Jewish
                Rabbi of <placeName>Wilkes Barre</placeName><lb/> preached a sermon last
                    <date>Saturday</date><lb/> and received about $20.00 for it.<lb/> It was a
                strange thing to me<lb/> to see a Radical Reformer<lb/> on <date>Friday</date>
                evening, where he acted<lb/> as Chasan here, singing Le cha Dodi<add>?</add><lb/>
                and recite Bameh Madlikin<add>?</add>.<lb/> Who is this <persName>Dr M.
                    Delbanco</persName><lb/> the Jewish Rabbi of<lb/>
                <placeName>Wilkes <sic>Barri</sic></placeName>, I can<lb/> not remember such a
                Rabbi</p>
            <pb n="4"/>
            <p rend="indent(1)">Be assured dear Sir<lb/> that I will still continue<lb/> to do
                anything for our holy<lb/> cause.</p>
            <p>Without further statements</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">I remain your<lb/> servant</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">
                <persName role="author">J. Oppenheim</persName>
            </p>
        </body>
